Question 2:

Create two new categorical variables in flights based on the departure time (dep_time), and arrival time (arr_time). These new variables should have four categories: âearly morningâ for 12am to 6am, âmorningâ for 6am to 12pm, âafternoonâ for 12pm to 6pm, and âeveningâ for 6pm to 12am. Show barplots of both of these new variables.

#step 1: convert HHMM to hours (e.g., 523 -> 5.38 ~ 5h23m)
time_to_hour <- function(x) {
  ifelse(is.na(x), NA,
         floor(x / 100) + (x %% 100) / 60)}

#step 2: Add categorical variables for dep_time and arr_time
flights_timecat <- flights %>%
  mutate(dep_hour = time_to_hour(dep_time),
         arr_hour = time_to_hour(arr_time),
         dep_period = case_when(
           dep_hour >= 0  & dep_hour < 6  ~ "early morning",
           dep_hour >= 6  & dep_hour < 12 ~ "morning",
           dep_hour >= 12 & dep_hour < 18 ~ "afternoon",
           dep_hour >= 18 & dep_hour < 24 ~ "evening",
           TRUE ~ NA_character_
         ),
         arr_period = case_when(
           arr_hour >= 0  & arr_hour < 6  ~ "early morning",
           arr_hour >= 6  & arr_hour < 12 ~ "morning",
           arr_hour >= 12 & arr_hour < 18 ~ "afternoon",
           arr_hour >= 18 & arr_hour < 24 ~ "evening",
           TRUE ~ NA_character_
         ))
##step 3: show barplots for the variables
# Plot departure period
ggplot(flights_timecat, aes(x = dep_period)) +
  geom_bar(fill = "steelblue") +
  labs(title = "Number of Flights by Departure Period",
       x = "Departure Period",
       y = "Count") +
  theme_minimal()
# Plot arrival period
ggplot(flights_timecat, aes(x = arr_period)) +
  geom_bar(fill = "darkblue") +
  labs(title = "Number of Flights by Arrival Period",
       x = "Arrival Period",
       y = "Count") +
  theme_minimal()
#step 4: Define red-eye flights
flights_timecat <- flights_timecat %>%
  mutate(red_eye = dep_period %in% c("afternoon", "evening") &
                     arr_period %in% c("early morning", "morning"))

#step 5: Calculate percentage of red-eye flights
red_eye_pct <- flights_timecat %>%
  summarise(percent_red_eye = mean(red_eye, na.rm = TRUE) * 100)
red_eye_pct

Question 5:

Create a new variable in the weather dataset by pasting together those 5 variables, then determine how many duplicated values there are and explain why.

# Create a unique variable 
weather_keyed <- weather %>%
  mutate(key = paste(year, month, day, hour, origin, sep = "-"))

# Count duplicates
dup_count <- sum(duplicated(weather_keyed$key))

dup_count
[1] 3

There are 3 duplicates, and the reason why there are duplicates is because there could be multiple observations per hour since weather is not recorded once per hour per origin. The weather data also includes a minute column, but by only adding hour to the key variable, we are collapsing all observations that correspond to the same hour.

names(weather)
 [1] "origin"     "year"       "month"      "day"        "hour"      
 [6] "temp"       "dewp"       "humid"      "wind_dir"   "wind_speed"
[11] "wind_gust"  "precip"     "pressure"   "visib"      "time_hour" 
weather_hourly_unique <- weather %>%
  distinct(origin, time_hour, .keep_all = TRUE)
flights_weather <- flights %>%
  left_join(weather_hourly_unique,
            by = c("origin", "time_hour"),
            suffix = c("_flight", "_weather"))

Question 8:

Compute the average delay by destination, then add that information to the airports data frame. Make a map showing the spatial distribution of delays (you can make it however you like, but we recommend using either ggplot or leaflet). Use the color of the points to display the average delay for each airport.

# 1) Average ARRIVAL delay by destination (dest)
avg_delay_dest <- flights %>%
  group_by(dest) %>%
  summarise(
    avg_arr_delay = mean(arr_delay, na.rm = TRUE), # excludes cancelled flights
    n = n(),
    .groups = "drop"
  ) %>%
  filter(!is.na(avg_arr_delay))

# 2) Join to airports metadata (match dest -> airports$faa)
airports_delay <- airports %>%
  select(faa, name, lat, lon) %>%
  inner_join(avg_delay_dest, by = c("faa" = "dest")) %>%
  filter(!is.na(lat), !is.na(lon))

library(leaflet)

pal <- colorNumeric(palette = "RdYlBu", domain = airports_delay$avg_arr_delay, reverse = TRUE)

leaflet(airports_delay) |>
  addTiles() |>
  addCircleMarkers(
    lng = ~lon, lat = ~lat,
    radius = ~pmax(3, pmin(12, sqrt(n)/4)),  # size by traffic
    color = ~pal(avg_arr_delay),
    stroke = FALSE, fillOpacity = 0.85,
    label = ~paste0(name, " (", faa, "): ", round(avg_arr_delay, 1), " min; n=", n)
  ) |>
  addLegend("bottomright", pal = pal, values = ~avg_arr_delay,
            title = "Avg arrival delay (min)", opacity = 1)

Question 9:

Create as many plots and summary statistics as needed to answer the primary question above.

# Merge flights + weather (hourly unique)
weather_hourly <- weather %>%
  { if ("minute" %in% names(.)) arrange(., origin, time_hour, minute) else . } %>%
  distinct(origin, time_hour, .keep_all = TRUE)

flw2 <- flights %>%
  left_join(weather_hourly, by = c("origin","time_hour")) %>%
  filter(!is.na(dep_delay))

#Define weather flags
low_press_cut <- quantile(flw2$pressure, 0.10, na.rm = TRUE)
flw2 <- flw2 %>%
  mutate(
    precip_any   = precip > 0,
    precip_heavy = precip >= 0.5,
    low_vis      = visib <= 2,
    wind_high    = wind_speed >= 20,
    gust_high    = wind_gust >= 35,
    freezing     = temp <= 32,
    low_pressure = pressure <= low_press_cut
  )

# Summary statistics
phenoms <- c("precip_any","precip_heavy","low_vis","wind_high",
             "gust_high","freezing","low_pressure")

effects_tbl <- lapply(phenoms, function(p) {
  df <- flw2 %>% filter(.data[[p]] %in% TRUE)  
  tibble(
    phenomenon   = p,
    n_true       = nrow(df),
    mean_delay   = mean(df$dep_delay, na.rm = TRUE),
    median_delay = median(df$dep_delay, na.rm = TRUE),
    sd_delay     = sd(df$dep_delay, na.rm = TRUE)
  )
}) %>% bind_rows() %>%
  arrange(desc(mean_delay))

top5 <- head(effects_tbl, 5)
top5
# A tibble: 5 Ã 5
  phenomenon   n_true mean_delay median_delay sd_delay
  <chr>         <int>      <dbl>        <dbl>    <dbl>
1 precip_heavy    149       48.5           18     77.7
2 precip_any    21086       30.9            5     59.2
3 low_vis        9730       28.0            2     59.6
4 low_pressure  29742       19.4            0     48.9
5 gust_high      4972       18.8            0     45.1
ggplot(top5, aes(x = reorder(phenomenon, mean_delay), y = mean_delay)) +
  geom_col() +
  coord_flip() +
  labs(title = "Top 5 Weather Phenomena Causing Flight Delays",
       x = "Phenomenon", y = "Average dep_delay (minutes)")

Conclusion: heavy precipitation is the weather phenomenon that had the greatest impact on flight delays.
